{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"3d593960-10da-489c-85e8-169bfcfc4f46","content":"The directory doesn't exist yet. No worries — here's what you need to configure in your `.csproj` to publish as a **dotnet tool** on NuGet.org:\n\n### Required `.csproj` properties\n\n```xml\n<PropertyGroup>\n  <OutputType>Exe</OutputType>\n  <TargetFramework>net8.0</TargetFramework>\n\n  <!-- These make it a dotnet tool -->\n  <PackAsTool>true</PackAsTool>\n  <ToolCommandName>my-mcp-server</ToolCommandName>\n\n  <!-- NuGet metadata -->\n  <PackageId>MyMcpServer</PackageId>\n  <Version>1.0.0</Version>\n  <Authors>YourName</Authors>\n  <Description>An MCP server for …</Description>\n  <PackageReadmeFile>README.md</PackageReadmeFile>\n  <PackageLicenseExpression>MIT</PackageLicenseExpression>\n</PropertyGroup>\n```\n\n### Key points\n\n1. **`PackAsTool=true`** — tells `dotnet pack` to produce a tool package.\n2. **`ToolCommandName`** — the CLI command users will invoke (e.g., `my-mcp-server`).\n3. **`OutputType=Exe`** — required for tools.\n\n### Publish workflow\n\n```bash\n# Pack\ndotnet pack -c Release\n\n# Push (get your API key from nuget.org/account/apikeys)\ndotnet nuget push bin/Release/MyMcpServer.1.0.0.nupkg \\\n  --api-key <YOUR_API_KEY> \\\n  --source https://api.nuget.org/v3/index.json\n```\n\n### Users install & run it with\n\n```bash\ndotnet tool install -g MyMcpServer\nmy-mcp-server            # runs via stdio\n```\n\nThat's all that's needed — `PackAsTool` + `ToolCommandName` are the critical pieces. Everything else is standard NuGet metadata.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"6b8b27eb-66da-43e1-99cb-e7fbecd9ee6e","outputTokens":498,"requestId":"2029:30FF5A:1634449:18E65E6:6A052252"},"id":"d94d1326-db7b-4d35-b462-ae1d37e009ea","timestamp":"2026-05-14T01:16:13.900Z","parentId":"91c85820-2058-4a66-894d-df1c7a45a0ab"}
